1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Good morning Mr. Anderson. It's a pleasure to be with you. Thank you for welcoming us to your home this morning.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:28,000
My name is Joe Winnier of the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

4
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:36,000
We're here in Bogolusianne to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:46,000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian, specifically the Smithsonian's Museum of African American History and Culture.

6
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:56,000
I am with colleague John Bishop, who is our videographer and the project curator from the National Museum.

7
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Ms. Lane Nichols is here as well. We are in Bogolusa with Mr. Fletcher Anderson and Mrs. Cynthia Anderson to talk about the movement and the deacons in the 50s, 60s and talk about all that history.

8
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Thank you again. It's going to be worth it. Thank you.

9
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:35,000
I thought I'd start if I would like to just or both would like to just reflect a little bit about say Bogolus in the late 50s and early 60s sort of set the context for the more active phase of local struggle level of emerge in the 64-65 period.

10
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:47,000
I was first interested in coming from the cross burning that happened in the 6th, when the Cookega clan burned across the Nau Yacht.

11
00:01:47,000 --> 00:02:03,000
That's really what got our attention to something was going on. From that point on, we definitely got involved with the Civil Rights Movement, making conditions better than what they were.

12
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:25,000
We were always aware that we were treated as second classes, but we were kind of in a fix where it was acceptable. But that we saw things changing and the rest of the world in laws begin to change.

13
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:37,000
We wanted to be a part of that change. And that cross burning come about because when I went to work at the Barf Act in 1962.

14
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:56,000
And then when I went to work at the Barf Act in 1962, they had separate everything, separate bathrooms, separate drinking fountain, separate doors that you go through to go into the Yacht, separate paylines, separate working places.

15
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:22,000
So I and some more of the employees were there wanting to make a difference. And first I started as a new employee, the black employees that were previously there had me to do things that they wouldn't do because I was a new employee as a new no better.

16
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:37,000
So I would go and drink out the water fountain attempt to take showers in a white bathroom. But for that bathroom because I would be turned around.

17
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:52,000
The water fountain that they found up and say, you're not supposed to do that. Well, the oldest black employee knew that I wasn't supposed to do that. It wasn't allowed. But since I was a new employee, they kind of had me to test that.

18
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:14,000
And at that point, we started filing lawsuits against our workplace. And we went to court along with the Robert Hicks, he filed a suit and we were just for the end of the suit. We all had to testify and fairly courted about our working condition.

19
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And from that point, things kind of opened up at the workplace concerned. We were able to work on job that black said never been able to work on.

20
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And we were able to get our black females employed at that plant, which had never happened before. And we were able to get supervisors in the plant that had never been before.

21
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:54,000
And this is when things really start getting heated up because that's the changes that they have never happened before. And sometimes changes hard to come back.

22
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:04,000
Because people get what's said in their own ways and get white employees that didn't want to make a change that they didn't want to see this happen.

23
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:20,000
So things got to be hard and sticky as we might say in Bogdallus. So that's when we left out of the plant, we got the plant pretty well situated but out in the streets in the community.

24
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And we were able to get it. Things were talked about and it was heated. We were dealing with a city that didn't hire black city workers.

25
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:54,000
And on the garbage truck, we didn't have a black person working. We didn't have a black person working. There was no elected people on the council or any form of government inside of the city of Limit of Bogdallus.

26
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:12,000
And these are the changes that we went about trying these things that we went about trying to change. And about doing that, we had many, many marches in Bogdallus in the city of Bogdallus until this city courthouse.

27
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:30,000
And we end up having to go to federal court to try to get some of these obstacles removed. And then doing that, we had to testify in federal court. Then we had to get an injunction against the police department in Bogdallus.

28
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:55,000
They keep them from brutalizing the black people of the city of Bogdallus. And we had to go, I was one of the one had to go and testify in federal court to make these things happen. I was participate in all of the, most of the changes that happened inside of the city of Bogdallus in the surrounding areas.

29
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:21,000
We didn't have no black policeman. I had the opportunity to sit down with the negotiating committee that put other, it's abusive from the AFL, from St. Louis, Anna that come in. And I presented three names.

30
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And out of those three names that I presented two of them was chosen to be the first black policeman of the city of Bogdallus.

31
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:45,000
Though three I presented with my classmates, the class of 1959, they also worked with me at the Barfract. And they were chosen to be the first black policeman of the city of Bogdallus.

32
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:56,000
And we had to get to injunction against the city of the police because they were terrorizing the black citizens of Bogdallus.

33
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:05,000
It was beating them as we were doing. So we went to court, we got to injunction so some of that ceased some of that seat.

34
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And then we marched to Frankerton three times to try to get some things open up in the Paris.

35
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:32,000
We marched one time and they didn't know good. We marched the second time and they didn't know good. Then we said we're going to take it to the government, Governor John McKithey in Badenburg.

36
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:47,000
So we marched to Badenburg and at that particular time we didn't get chance to see the governor. He wasn't meet with. But they began to get so heated up.

37
00:08:47,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Then he flew into Bogdallus and we had a meeting with him at the airport. And I was able to sit down and be a part of that meeting with him.

38
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:08,000
And we went on a lot of things and a few things opened up for us through that meeting.

39
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:29,000
But we kept the pressure on. We kept it. We kept marching. We kept picketing. We kept demonstrating. And men, a lot of more of the blacks we would picket marches to let them open up and give black people's job employment.

40
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:41,000
And as we kept pushing on them and the black quit shopping in their stores, they began to open up and high. And so we were successful there.

41
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:52,000
And most of the thing that we did, we were successful in open up employment for our people.

42
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:55,000
This is an interesting, do you want to have a little audience with us?

43
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,000
Yes, I'm a little bit.

44
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,000
It's a wonderful start. Thank you.

45
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
It will be a lot of history.

46
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:07,000
Sandy, do you want to start with some of your early recollections?

47
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:16,000
My first interest was when they burnt it, grossed a million.

48
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:19,000
Did you remember what happened?

49
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:22,000
Well, I know it was 63.

50
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Yeah, about 63.

51
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:34,000
And when he left work, he was safe in the plant.

52
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:45,000
But when he left work between the plant and home, they would attack him. And they kept calling them Bob Hicks.

53
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:52,000
So he came home one evening and he said, come on, I want you to go with me.

54
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:59,000
I said, where are you going? I'm going to find out who this person I'm about to die for.

55
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:03,000
So we found out what they lived and we went to the Hicks's home.

56
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:05,000
You hadn't known them at that point?

57
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:08,000
I knew her.

58
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:12,000
But I had never had any kind of conversation or relationship with her.

59
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:20,000
And when we went, we got to their house and I walked into those, she asked me for my driver's license.

60
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
I gave him to.

61
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And from that point, we were a team.

62
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Yeah.

63
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:37,000
Man, ask a little bit, just a little bit more about the longer background.

64
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:43,000
Could you each say a little bit about your family and your parents?

65
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:47,000
Well, my grandfather was George Anderson.

66
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:50,000
My grandmother was Maggie Anderson.

67
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:53,000
And they were Spaniards and Bogdars.

68
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:04,000
They eventually came from Mississippi, which is a street Mississippi.

69
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:13,000
And they left street Mississippi and came to Bogdaluccia looking for a better opportunity and for workplace.

70
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:17,000
Because they had to paper me or here, they had to buy a factory here.

71
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:20,000
And they were looking for an employee.

72
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,000
My grandmother, she went into real estate.

73
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:29,000
And my grandfather, he ended up being a taxidrop in that was his employee.

74
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:36,000
He was one of the first black people to register vote and watch the parade.

75
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:41,000
And he was always active in civil rights.

76
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:48,000
And he had to help to elevate the blacks during that particular time.

77
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:52,000
He was very instrumental in helping that to come back.

78
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:56,000
My grandmother, she had a borders.

79
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:01,000
People that come into town, she roamed and boarded.

80
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,000
Rooms and fed them.

81
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:11,000
And they worked at these different jobs and embeholders.

82
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:14,000
And you were carrying bolus?

83
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:16,000
Oh, yeah.

84
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:20,000
Right, he had bolus.

85
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,000
Grandparents, they were really good finally.

86
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:27,000
They were property owners.

87
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:31,000
And my grandfather, he attended college.

88
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:35,000
My grandmother, she attended college.

89
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:39,000
And my mother was a very smart woman too.

90
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:45,000
But she was, my grandmother became ill and my mother singing after her.

91
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:49,000
That's basically what she did to care of her mother.

92
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:54,000
But they were wonderful, wonderful people.

93
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,000
And I married a sentient year baker.

94
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And out of that reunion, we had three kids.

95
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:12,000
It was Sonia, Annison, Gamble, Annison, and Patrick, Annison.

96
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:17,000
And Sonia, she is blessed to have a wonderful daughter.

97
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:23,000
Gamble, she is blessed to have two wonderful grandchildren from him.

98
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:29,000
And they reside now in Dallas, Texas.

99
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:35,000
And my son, he is in Mount Harmon, Louisiana.

100
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:38,000
What did your grandparents go to college?

101
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
Oh, come.

102
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:42,000
My grandfather, what did Oh, come?

103
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:43,000
Purely.

104
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:49,000
This is actually, do you want to share some recollections of your family history?

105
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:51,000
Did you also grow up in the movies?

106
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,000
My history is my different from his.

107
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:03,000
My father was a Janine Lewis Baker senior.

108
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:13,000
And my mother was Esther V. Watson.

109
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:16,000
My mother was from Franklin, Louisiana.

110
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:24,000
My dad was from Zachary, Louisiana.

111
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:31,000
We grew up, I grew up in the middle quarters.

112
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:40,000
And we were considered the poets of the Black people.

113
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:47,000
We were outdoors, people, type people, we hunt, fish.

114
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:53,000
When I got in the seventh grade, my basketball coach told me to go ask my mom

115
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,000
to play basketball.

116
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:00,000
And when I went to talk to her, she didn't even turn around.

117
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,000
She said, yeah, as long as you make Donald Row.

118
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:09,000
I made Donald Row from then on.

119
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:16,000
I had a good life growing up in Vogue of Loosen when I found out how people really felt about me.

120
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:19,000
It hurt.

121
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:22,000
And then I wanted to fight back.

122
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:28,000
And when they disavigated the schools in 54, I had a whole group of girls ready to go on over to the high school

123
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:32,000
and take care of that little disavigation.

124
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:38,000
But the teachers liked to have a hard time.

125
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:47,000
Tell me a little bit about Mr. Armstrong, your decision to seek a job at the Vogue's factory.

126
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:52,000
And what your job was at factory and what it was like to work in there?

127
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:59,000
Yeah, when I first went there, my first job by working in the shipping department,

128
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:02,000
I was what you call a loader.

129
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:07,000
That's load in Vogue's car than trucks too.

130
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:11,000
And from that, I went to a trucker.

131
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:19,000
That's when you promoted to drive a folk rail and do the loadin' with folk rail.

132
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And I left that and moved to another department which called the cargator.

133
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And I went on a job there as a takeoff person.

134
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:41,000
And I moved from the takeoff person to a slitter operator.

135
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:47,000
And I moved from that to a first helpful.

136
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:57,000
And I left that position to go to an overhead crane operator.

137
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,000
And although the job will help prove to the head,

138
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:05,000
oh, but the takeoff person will help by white employees.

139
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:11,000
And I was able to work myself through that line and it wasn't easy.

140
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:21,000
Because when you really had to be trained by a person that you was going to eventually replace them.

141
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:26,000
And that's not easy. That's not easy for anybody to do.

142
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:29,000
You can imagine about how much training you would get.

143
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:35,000
So we basically had to basically train ourselves.

144
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,000
And the hard thing about when I went to the overhead crane operator,

145
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:42,000
I didn't have no training whatsoever.

146
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:45,000
I had to train myself on them.

147
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:50,000
And that's a dangerous job to overhead rail in the crane operator.

148
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:55,000
And that is the job that I basically got injured on,

149
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:00,000
probably the lack of training that I had to retire from.

150
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
But to get a change in that buffer,

151
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:05,000
I could go and not back to that workplace.

152
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:06,000
So we had to walk.

153
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:10,000
I had to walk in some of our other,

154
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:13,000
pick it on our own company.

155
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:15,000
And that's not easy.

156
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:16,000
Walk and pick it on your company.

157
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:22,000
And then you got to put your pick it down and punch in and go to work for the same people that you got there.

158
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:26,000
So you could imagine how to tension in the thing.

159
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:33,000
It was tough.

160
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:41,000
And we went on to,

161
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:46,000
I was wondering what I was thinking about when we went to the Meredith March,

162
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:53,000
when Jay Meredith got jumped on when he was going back to Ole Miss

163
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:56,000
for reunion of some sort.

164
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:04,000
And we were the acts as a deacons to come and protect the March.

165
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:06,000
And from the time that we got there,

166
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:10,000
we were able to march a man with no incident after that.

167
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:16,000
And that was during the time because we were very good at what we did protecting people.

168
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:21,000
We protected our neighborhoods that stopped people from driving by,

169
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:25,000
shooting up in the houses and beating them.

170
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:26,000
We had walker talkers.

171
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:27,000
We had come,

172
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:32,000
thing that commute with one another all through the community.

173
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:33,000
We know where everybody at.

174
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,000
We know we had block captains.

175
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,000
We had everything set or anything.

176
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:42,000
If anybody coming in there, we were able to block the streets up.

177
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Because we had to be our own protection because the police were not there to protect us.

178
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:53,000
They were there to protect the crew crew.

179
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:00,000
How did you first hear about the deacons or become a member of the deacons?

180
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:08,000
First we were there sitting around and somebody came from Joan Burl.

181
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:18,000
And we were talking to us and I was in that meeting and it was talking about how they were able to form the solidification.

182
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,000
We become a charter member of it.

183
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:24,000
You had that very diverse meeting and that worried?

184
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,000
That's right.

185
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:27,000
That's right.

186
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,000
It was with Joan Burl.

187
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:32,000
And it sounded pretty good to us.

188
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
Tell me what you remember from that meeting.

189
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:37,000
I think they were Ernest Thomas and Fred Kirkpatrick.

190
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:38,000
That's right.

191
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:47,000
And I remember sitting there on the many days explaining what they did in Joan Burl and how they did it and what we needed to do.

192
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:54,000
And from that meeting we just kind of bowed into it.

193
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:58,000
And then we just kind of set up our own deacon for defense.

194
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
And I was eventually kind of overshadowed there.

195
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:05,000
But it was a ridden that came from Joan Burl.

196
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:09,000
Had you grown up using a right-wing shotgun to hunt or how did you...

197
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:11,000
Yeah, we all been hunters.

198
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:12,000
We all been hunters.

199
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:14,000
We know how to hunt.

200
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,000
We know how to take care of weapons.

201
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:17,000
We know all of that.

202
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:19,000
But that's the honest reason.

203
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:26,000
I had never shot at a person or nothing like that because we never did.

204
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:29,000
We're always a little bit low-bought in citizens.

205
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:32,000
We knew your body.

206
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:36,000
We come up and our elders will tell us what certain things you can do.

207
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:38,000
Certain things you can't do this and not for you.

208
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:42,000
Just don't do that because they were basically trying to keep us out of trouble.

209
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:46,000
And trouble needed to get into.

210
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:55,000
Because one time I was me in three of my civil right workers was coming out of the restaurant at Agna Cafe.

211
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:05,000
And I walked out of the cafe and somebody was on the side of me in the dark and hit me with some weapon.

212
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:18,000
