Milton Johnson was getting attacked by the law.

739
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:19,000
That's right.

740
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:20,000
Milton Johnson.

741
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:23,000
Oh, had it too.

742
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:26,000
Was that when they attacked had it?

743
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:27,000
The little girl.

744
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:30,000
Yeah, had it.

745
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:38,000
And I remember one occasion we was picking it on public property.

746
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:42,000
I mean, Robert Hicks and a bunch of more of us.

747
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:44,000
And they arrested us.

748
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:48,000
And put us in school bus and killed us at St. Tamin' Day.

749
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:52,000
Well, the bus broke down, threw the rod on the way to St. Tamin' Day.

750
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:57,000
So we had to set it on the bus and wait till they brought another bus.

751
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:01,000
And that was one of the detectives.

752
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:04,000
It was one of the things where we was on public property.

753
00:54:04,000 --> 00:54:06,000
Nobody, no private property.

754
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:09,000
Nothing came of that bus load of us.

755
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:11,000
Nothing came of that.

756
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:13,000
No charge, no fines, no nothing.

757
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:15,000
It's been a long-distance.

758
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:16,000
It was me for it.

759
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:21,000
Our lawyers come in and got everything.

760
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:22,000
It's me.

761
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:23,000
We just walked out of jail.

762
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:24,000
That was it.

763
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:26,000
Never heard no more about it.

764
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:30,000
Let's take a little call on St. Tamin.

765
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:38,000
Well, you know, some of the people that were there, how would you tell them that?

766
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:41,000
Yeah, well, some of the people, like I say, were with us.

767
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:44,000
Was Willie Jane Preston.

768
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:48,000
And his brother Oliver Preston.

769
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:53,000
And they were very, very active in the move.

770
00:54:53,000 --> 00:55:00,000
There was women like Helen Jefferson.

771
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:04,000
A guy by name was Jane Brown.

772
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:09,000
And they were Canadian Griffith.

773
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:12,000
And they were very, very men.

774
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:19,000
Canadian Griffith was the one that used to pick up Jane Farmer from Corp when he come in.

775
00:55:19,000 --> 00:55:22,000
And we would pick him up from the airport.

776
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:25,000
We would protect him while he was here.

777
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:30,000
We would protect his workers, the core workers, the civil right workers while he was here.

778
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:33,000
Mace, you know, danger come to him.

779
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:36,000
That was Canadian Griffith in my job.

780
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:39,000
That's what we were assigned to.

781
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:46,000
And all the top people that would come in, we were the one that watched them.

782
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:49,000
We were the one that protected.

783
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:53,000
Canadian Griffith in there myself during that time.

784
00:55:53,000 --> 00:56:02,000
And he was, Canadian Griffith attacked on Columbus Street in front of Windixie.

785
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:05,000
Windixie was on Columbus Street.

786
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:10,000
They beat him up pretty badly.

787
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:14,000
And nothing was ever come to that.

788
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:22,000
Any time that something would happen to a black person, they would never do anything about it.

789
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:30,000
We had one idea of friends, museums coming from the military, Captain Seymour,

790
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:39,000
making a phone call in a phone booth right there on Columbus Street,

791
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:43,000
playing the shot in a phone booth.

792
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:53,000
Nothing, Maca-Mayor had to come to Boa-Luisa to see if nothing never happened to that.

793
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:56,000
And we were this open game.

794
00:56:56,000 --> 00:57:00,000
And he much with the protection that we were given.

795
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:06,000
Some people come down like Seymour, he went away out of what was happening here.

796
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:10,000
And he went to the phone booth, Maca-Mayor called all of this happened to him.

797
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:15,000
He is in the military fighting for this country and get shot.

798
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:17,000
Yeah, they'll do one thing.

799
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:26,000
Can you share your recollections of folks in Corps and the collaboration between the League and Corps?

800
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:30,000
It was great. It was great.

801
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:33,000
They was a life saver to us.

802
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:40,000
And it came, it was a lot of knowledge too, because they were for Mars and Demonstrates and all that kind of thought.

803
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:50,000
They were very knowledgeable of what to do and how to do it, and how to stay out of harm's way.

804
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:53,000
How to protect yourself.

805
00:57:53,000 --> 00:58:01,000
They were very loud. And Jane from, I don't know what we did that meant for him.

806
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:03,000
I have so much respect for him.

807
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:07,000
And Dick Gregory and all of them, they would come in and they would help us.

808
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:14,000
They would help us to raise money and do, and have to keep the movement going.

809
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:19,000
You Dick Gregory was a life saver too. You were very helpful too.

810
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:30,000
They talked to black people, or popular stuff, how to stop a pattern that had been set or established.

811
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:42,000
And instead of buying a Cadillac by a both-way, and drive that until you could buy your Cadillac, you could afford it.

812
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:51,000
They emphasize, don't make the other man fat off your label.

813
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:55,000
That your label worked for you.

814
00:58:55,000 --> 00:59:05,000
And as far as Dickens are concerned, when we won't outweigh the Baton Rouge, we got to Hamlin.

815
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:07,000
On March, on the road?

816
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:08,000
Yes.

817
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:15,000
And we decided we were going to spend a night in the park, in Greenville Park.

818
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:21,000
And that's where the football field was for Black High School.

819
00:59:22,000 --> 00:59:31,000
And the police department, the sheriff department, came down from Hamlin from Tenshville, O'Parrison, told us that we could not stay there.

820
00:59:31,000 --> 00:59:37,000
That that was private property.

821
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:45,000
So we told the police that, okay, we'll march up to Southeast and University and we spend the night there.

822
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:47,000
We paid taxes.

823
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:50,000
So that's somewhere we can't spend a night.

824
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:56,000
Well, they discussed it and they decided it was all right to stay in the park.

825
00:59:56,000 --> 01:00:03,000
We circled the cars in the park like the wagons and the Indians.

826
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:06,000
And they sent state troopers.

827
01:00:06,000 --> 01:00:12,000
Now, the state troopers were there to guard us, not protect us.

828
01:00:13,000 --> 01:00:17,000
And we spent the night in the park.

829
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:23,000
But the next morning they went to search all the black people's cars.

830
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:28,000
And that was the one time that I was proud as a Dicas Cossi.

831
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:37,000
When we were on at March, we didn't have, people would let us use the Baton.

832
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:39,000
We couldn't drink water.

833
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:42,000
We had to provide all our own needs.

834
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:47,000
So Mr. Wilde built a latrine on the back of a truck.

835
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:54,000
And he and his wife drove the latrine that's Bernadine's mama and daddy.

836
01:00:54,000 --> 01:01:00,000
The...

837
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:08,000
When we came out of that march and I came out of the park and headed toward the Baton

838
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:11,000
Rooie, they sent me home.

839
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:14,000
The rest of me headed toward Baton Rooie's.

840
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:18,000
But when I went that way the next day, they had tax.

841
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:23,000
It's thick as rocks, for miles on that walkway.

842
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:26,000
On that Rooie going to Baton Rooie's.

843
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:29,000
Client and put down all that, almost 10.

844
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:32,000
Yep.

845
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:35,000
Did you...

846
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:47,000
What was your sense of the clan in the community after finally the federal government came in

847
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:52,000
and really came down on the lawsuit?

848
01:01:52,000 --> 01:02:00,000
And did you have a sense that things had shifted in an important way or no?

849
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:03,000
But on the thing you have at that point, they were...

850
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:06,000
Someone was exposed.

851
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:09,000
We knew who they were.

852
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:12,000
You know, they was identified.

853
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:15,000
The federal government had identified.

854
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:18,000
Because some of my work with...

855
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:21,000
Oh, my job.

856
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:24,000
And some of them was...

857
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:26,000
My...

858
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:29,000
Supervised.

859
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:35,000
When you know you that you're supervised as a client, and he did.

860
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:39,000
And you could see him taking up money to send to the...

861
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:45,000
to help the Cluco clan and to fight out here and the streets of the state.

862
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:51,000
And you work in there and you have to take all this from you, supervised, whatever you tell you you have to do.

863
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:55,000
And you got to respect him, whatever.

864
01:02:55,000 --> 01:03:00,000
As telling you what to do, you have to respect that.

865
01:03:00,000 --> 01:03:01,000
Because we don't do that.

866
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:02,000
They need to do your job.

867
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:05,000
We can't support your family.

868
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:08,000
And we have to always keep that in mind too.

869
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:10,000
Always keep that in mind too.

870
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:12,000
At the workplace.

871
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:16,000
But one thing about who I work with, all is what you did outside the plant.

872
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:17,000
That was your business loan.

873
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:20,000
You were able to report back to work.

874
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:26,000
They didn't penalize you for what you did outside of the plant.

875
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:28,000
That's your business.

876
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:32,000
We could do anything we wanted to do for our activity for March.

877
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:37,000
And they might hold it, but they couldn't take your job from that.

878
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:38,000
They didn't do that.

879
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:39,000
Because you didn't do that.

880
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:40,000
That's why we had a scrum.

881
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:44,000
But if they took the time we had two years, we had a white year and a black year.

882
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:47,000
And there are some of the things that we were able to do that.

883
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:49,000
Merges that make it one.

884
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:50,000
Through the loss of the plant.

885
01:03:50,000 --> 01:03:51,000
Yeah.

886
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:57,000
And that made it, when we all come together, that made things a lot easier.

887
01:03:57,000 --> 01:04:01,000
It didn't help education though.

888
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:02,000
That's a great point.

889
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:03,000
And I want to ask that woman.

890
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:04,000
I take you back.

891
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:07,000
You were shaking your head a moment ago when I asked the question,

892
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:09,000
did it feel like much had changed?

893
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
Have federal government come down on the client?

894
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,000
And you were shaking your head?

895
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:14,000
No.

896
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:16,000
No.

897
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:27,000
In Bogalosa, when they make an announcement, you could tell from the location whether it's

898
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:30,000
black folk and a team.

899
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:33,000
You're not welcome.

900
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:42,000
All they want you to do is shop in town.

901
01:04:42,000 --> 01:04:51,000
And that's the most essential way the community can really change through the 60s and beyond.

902
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:56,000
It's just town, dad, to keep from changing.

903
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:59,000
Literally, dad.

904
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:02,000
You would see the street, drive down the street.

905
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:07,000
He's dead.

906
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:14,000
For the education, to my knowledge is that at first, he was separate.

907
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:21,000
You know, we were getting books to come from the white school.

908
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:29,000
But when we integrated, we still don't, we read not the same book we have in math and everything.

909
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:30,000
It's the same.

910
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:32,000
But we own the same level.

911
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:36,000
From that point, I think things are better.

912
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:50,000
But although we, my first last regulation was we are 60-40 in the school system, black

913
01:05:50,000 --> 01:05:51,000
kids.

914
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:53,000
60% black, 40% white.

915
01:05:53,000 --> 01:05:56,000
But we're not in control or nothing.

916
01:05:56,000 --> 01:06:00,000
You know, the school, but it's predominantly white.

917
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:10,000
The principals and system principals and everybody in the thought is predominantly white.

918
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:19,000
So even some of the whites in Bowel's hash sent their children to the parlor.

919
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:27,000
They won't even send them to public school because they said they can't get a good education in a system

920
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:30,000
because they don't say they quit teaching.

921
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:32,000
That's what they're being said.

922
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:33,000
They quit teaching.

923
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:34,000
They quit teaching anybody.

924
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:35,000
So they send them.

925
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:38,000
They owe them up a lot of private schools.

926
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:44,000
In the city of Kiesa, private school because they don't trust the public school system.

927
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:55,000
And by integrating, we kind of own the same level for us being in the same school, the same books.

928
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:04,000
And it helped the relationship of the young people with each other.

929
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:09,000
They can see what their parents are told down through these.

930
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:10,000
That's not so.

931
01:07:10,000 --> 01:07:13,000
That's not the kind of people they are.

932
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:14,000
They are good people.

933
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:15,000
They come from good home.

934
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:16,000
They are this.

935
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:21,000
And that relationship with them is a lot better.

936
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:27,000
And I think that comes from the integration of the school system.

937
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:35,000
They hired a lot of teachers that are not qualified.

938
01:07:35,000 --> 01:07:44,000
You got the biggest group when you go to a college graduation is the dual education people.

939
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:48,000
And when they came out, looked like all of them gained a book.

940
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:51,000
And got hired.

941
01:07:51,000 --> 01:08:02,000
Now, when they first used to go to school, white teachers who could not stand the thought of teaching black kids retired.

942
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:10,000
Some teachers stayed and they could not stand the thought of teaching black kids.

943
01:08:10,000 --> 01:08:14,000
And they talked to white kids and they changed the method of teaching.

944
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:20,000
Teachers used to stand in front of the class and teach everybody and everybody learned.

945
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:31,000
After these segregation, the teachers had to walk up and down the aisle and pay attention to individual students and correct them.

946
01:08:31,000 --> 01:08:34,000
They did not correct the black kids.

947
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:37,000
They just continued to go wrong.

948
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:50,000
Then they would end up in a village, special education and more than that.

949
01:08:50,000 --> 01:08:59,000
All of these things hindered true education.

950
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:04,000
And it's still hindered.

951
01:09:04,000 --> 01:09:07,000
Do you have final thoughts?

952
01:09:07,000 --> 01:09:11,000
We haven't talked about our relaying.

953
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:15,000
Do you have thoughts?

954
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:18,000
Do you have the last issues or what?

955
01:09:18,000 --> 01:09:20,000
I actually do.

956
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:22,000
Because we do everything different.

957
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:27,000
If you could change anything that you do, it's like changing.

958
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:31,000
I could change anything.

959
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:41,000
What I would like to see that it comes a time when we see each other as a person.

960
01:09:41,000 --> 01:09:48,000
When they're not in color of the skin, not anything to do that.

961
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:52,000
We would see a person as a person for what he is.

962
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:56,000
Before I would, and that's what I would like to see.

963
01:09:56,000 --> 01:09:58,000
That's a change that I would like to see.

964
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:00,000
Will I ever see it?

965
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:03,000
I guess seem like there going to always be racism.

966
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:10,000
I guess there will racism from the time that the country will never, ever form.

967
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:14,000
I can see it every day and then news for me here.

968
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:17,000
I can see it every day in the bubble.

969
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:23,000
At the workplace, what makes it, I don't know.

970
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:25,000
But I tell you one thing.

971
01:10:25,000 --> 01:10:28,000
We're going to fight to make, try to make a change.

972
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:31,000
We're going to fight to try to make a change.

973
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:36,000
All these changes that we have made so far, I know it was just a help of the good Lord

974
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:42,000
that kept us here because we have been in some battle.

975
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:44,000
We need much that much to bad news.

976
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:50,000
We have to, it will fight all the way there.

977
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:56,000
And it got so bad at one time, we got to have where there they wanted us to go.

978
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:02,000
Take 55 and go up through them with comb and come back home.

979
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:07,000
And at that time, we still stayed true for that.

